we provide predictions with explanations for all paralog pairs here (https://t.co/Oo6rnSOvFJ). Previous thread has all the details on what makes a a paralog pair likely to be synthetic lethal https://t.co/azvP6yRd3k

we originally built our classifier using synthetic lethal pairs derived from @CancerDepMap single gene CRISPR screens in >700 cell lines. we now show that this classifier can predict the consensus results from the four combinatorial CRISPR screens with good accuracy https://t.co/PqXR8wri4r

given the challenges created by genetic heterogeneity within and between tumours, synthetic lethals observed across multiple cell lines are likely to be of greater value as therapeutic targets than cell line specific hits so we  focussed our efforts on predicting them.

there is also significant variation across studies ‚Äì on average only ~30% of hits are shared between any given pair of studies. that's after restricting our analysis to those pairs that could be in common (i.e. screened in both studies) https://t.co/gbJQOElHh4

in total ~5% of paralog pairs have been tested for synthetic lethality in at least one cell line. we find that within studies there is significant variation across cell lines (most hits are only synthetic lethal in a single cell line). https://t.co/rQv4fu5aTt

in the last year 4 combinatorial CRISPR screens have been published with a focus on paralogs (from @TGonatopoulos @TraverHart @aliceb_phd and our co-author @David_J_Adams). These all test hundreds of paralog pairs for synthetic lethality in multiple cell lines.

an updated version of @dekegelb's work predicting synthetic lethal interactions between paralogs in cancer. our focus was always on predicting robust synthetic lethals (those that operate across multiple cell lines) but now we clarify why that's important https://t.co/ZduTN0WJkK

Sometimes its interesting to examine the origins of our biases and questions their validity. These biases are unlikely to go away soon, the public expect the person in the tie, with the "right" voice to be more authoritativeHowever we must ask what we do to counter that bias.

In hospitals, in government, in places of power, leaders dress in a suit because it commands respect. It is associated with authority. Should a suit and tie be business attire in a diverse inclusive world?

The tie/ suit represents a specific culture. Rawiri Waititi, a Maori politician recently challenged the tie in the NZ parliament dress code. He questioned the colonial origins of its proper attire.  He called the tie a colonial noose around his neck https://t.co/em6W6DLL3d

In the 1800s, the suit and necktie become shorthand for authority;  ties were not suitable for manual workers.  Ties remain  a symbol of male authority;  red for Republicans, blue for Democrats. There are interesting theories on the necktie length.. https://t.co/H17Y9MwfxO https://t.co/hEJ12Kcfza

What other bygone symbols of colonial authority  dominate our cultural "expectations" of what leaders look like? The tie is a classic symbol of class and authority. Aristocratic in origin , ties emerged in 17th century France when aristocrats adopted the cravat

Accent association with education are vestiges of a time when only the wealthy could access education. Surely the association between authority and accent are outdated.  With greater access to education, it should not be used as a proxy for professional education or authority

Is there a authoritative accent?  The trusted male media or news personality is an accident of early technology. Early radio distorted the voice, making it a few octave higher, so men came to dominate the airwaves and the male voice became the trusted voice on the radio.

Jamila Lyiscott makes a strong case for the  impact of language and accent discrimination in the USA. We judge people based on how they talk not what they say. This is also true in the UK where Etonian accents dominate Westminster and leadership positions https://t.co/E7D692aGvT

This snub was shocking, but often a snub is  subconscious. Someone's voice is given less consideration because the speaker "doesn't look or speak" like a leader.   The powerful Ted talk by Jamila Lyiscott is worth a listen https://t.co/ZB7TzdKLq9

We all have a subconscious bias of what leadership looks like based on our "cultural norms".   This week the 1st female European Commission president suffered a chair snub during a summit with male leaders in Turkey. https://t.co/MEmMUyUt3G

At present, I'm not aware of these sub lineages being associated with any epidemiological or clinical significance. These posts are just to provide information, and not to ring any alarm bells.

B.1.617.3: These were originally assigned into the lineage B.1.596, presumably because of the mutation N:P67S. They also are the same set of samples which were mentioned by @arambaut in the tweet here, with a 29nt deletion in ORF3a.https://t.co/Gn7ItMCB3L

B.1.617.2: This sub lineage has "lost" one of the two mutations of concern, E484Q, and mutated back to the original. While not as large as B.1.617.1, these sequences are also in large frequency (112/603, or ~19% of all B.1.617 seqs on GISAID currently)https://t.co/MUlkD7vITI

B.1.617.1: The largest sub lineage, and has both the original mutations of concern, L452R and E484Q. Even the subset of samples with the third mutation of concern, V382L, also fall into this lineagehttps://t.co/Qtbb3v1g34

In fact, because workshops often tackle a narrow 'niche' of researchers, it's very likely that you'll get concentrated feedback exactly from people who could end up your future reviewers or even collaborators. :) 14/15

Workshops typically have a much higher (~75+%) acceptance rate, are a great platform to get feedback on your work before it is publication-ready, and---somewhat ironically---the fact that they are attached to a major conference means you still get a lot of exposure. 13/15

But one piece of advice I'd give is, once you have a meaningful hypothesis and maybe 1-2 small experiments verifying it in certain conditions, to always submit your work to a relevant **workshop**. 12/15

I think it's a bit of a sad reality that students are driven to "publish or perish". If you work on problems that you find highly meaningful, with a niche that will find your solutions valuable, I don't find it an absolute requirement that the work must be published. 11/15

Once your model fits the hardcoded problem correctly, you can gradually relax the 'restricted' data you feed it, making sure it still works every step of the way.This was an impactful workflow that proved critical in many of my recent algorithmic reasoning papers. 10/15

By this I mean, for example, directly feeding to the model data it is not supposed to have, to the point where if the model doesn't work in this setting, you  (usually) either have a bug somewhere or the hypothesis is very likely false. 9/15

I regularly attend meetings with the Family Genomics research group led by @lornahoulihan at @MaynoothUni. The research interests of the group include the genetic basis of neurodevelopmental disorders and sleep disruption in families with autism.

Genomics of Brain Disorders (Wellcome) - a conference to learn and compare approaches used to study psychiatric disorders, like schizophrenia and depression, and neurodegenerative disorders such as Alzheimer‚Äôs disease.
Autism Research ThesisInThree - a day for early career researchers to present their research to the public and other researchers across Ireland, organised by @FianaNG in support of AsIAm.
World Congress of Psychiatric Genetics - an international conference covering genetic discoveries in psychiatric disorders with talks from speakers in psychiatry, neuroscience and genetics.
Sleep, circadian rhythms and mental health in schools (SCRAMS) @SCRAMS15 - a mini-conference outlining multi-disciplinary research in sleep and its effect on mental well-being in adolescents.

The B.1.617 variant has certain concerning mutations, such as E484Q and L452R in the Spike protein. These have shown evidence of reduced neutralization via monoclonal Ab assays, but vaccine-induced immunity is by definition polyclonal and included T-cell response.

On the #VOC variant of concern B.1.617: it has been spotted at low levels in India for several months, but the B.1.1.7 variant was more prevalent, which probably means the former is less transmissible than the latter in normal circumstances.

The SG-NEx data was designed to enable the benchmarking of the long read RNA-Seq technology, but also to provide a resource that will hopefully fuel computational methods development.
Nanopore also enables the direct sequencing of RNAs including their modifications, which can be computationally identified without any additional experiment. https://t.co/hD9RbqKNAL

Long reads increase the accuracy for read-to-transcript assignment, they allow the analysis of long-range splicing associations, enable the analysis of individual fusion isoforms, and help to detect more repetitive transcripts.

If you are only interested in gene expression, it might actually not make a big difference (there is also microarrays by the way). In other scenarios, expect a difference, that is where long reads are very likely to help. https://t.co/AZZqt4kWeW

First of all, if you want to study the transcriptome, you want to use long reads (they are designed for this). Sometimes that is not possible (throughput, RNA input requirements, and no experience in data processing and analysis are the most obvious reasons).

I‚Äôm still digesting what this all means for me and how I deal with it going forward. I obviously can‚Äôt not be #ActuallyAutistic me - there isn‚Äôt something I can do to ‚Äúfunction‚Äù differently.That‚Äôs it - no great insights from me. Just thought worth sharing #AutismAcceptanceMonth
Just to be sure, this reaction isn‚Äôt restricted to men of course - many women allow men to ‚Äúbe smart‚Äù or direct, but not other women.

When things got rough, I have been told ‚ÄúLook, you‚Äôre an intelligent girl and want to have a career..‚Äù, basically offering me the chance to *just smile*. (I was a 39 year old experienced professional and mother at the time. I also did not understand what I was being told to do.)

Or the big boss looking livid when I had figured out a massive issue before his same-aged, older white male colleague who was supposed to know about it (kudos to the latter, who didn‚Äôt mind at all and acknowledged my contribution).

Memorable moments include an older, white, male colleague interrupting me to assert, hectically, ‚Äúmy brain is faster than yours, you know?‚Äù, when I was simply summarizing a situation and suggesting steps to take.
Or, worse, describing an issue in detail that most have just started to sense is a thing, and then moving on to suggestions for how to solve it (the horror).

So I inadvertently drop thought/knowledge/truth bombs all the time. Saying that thing in meetings that most are thinking, and which *clearly* needs to be discussed to make progress, but for some reason nobody says out loud.

‚ÄúI'll be nice to you and smileBut I'll hate you all the while.‚ÄùI read this from an #ActuallyAustistic perspective and it describes so well what I am literally incapable of.I can only do my thing and use my brain and never hide it - but of course that‚Äôs not allowed.

I love this: "Science and journalism are kindred pursuits. Both seek to gather information, understand it, and convey its meaning to others. It makes sense that journalists would be drawn to do science, and such mergers have often resulted in truly compelling work."

"Newsrooms should also implement a process of peer review. Although data stories may be fact-checked, and reporters often consult scientists for input on in-house analyses, the ultimate gatekeeper is typically the editor, who is seldom a scientist."
To be honest, that kind of reproducibility is not even achieved in the academic literature at this time, and is generally good practice for both academics and newsrooms.

He compares & contrasts analyses done by data journalists vs. academics.  Speed of production is obviously different (journalists can churn out more). However, there is the issue of proper vetting. @cabrerosic proposes that all data and code be released with news publications.

"Gone are the days when science journalism was like sports journalism, where the action was watched from the press box and simply conveyed. News outlets have stepped onto the field. They are doing the science themselves." What does this mean?

This is a bit of a brain dump of things I've been thinking and reading about recently, if you read all the way here thank you and would love to hear your thoughts!

So we have somewhat converged on how we talk about dynamics. What I think is missing is how we to talk about and infer causality in these systems, where uncertainty reigns and many many variables are involved (Where art thou structure learning?)

Some shared, qualitative language across frameworks describing these systems (master equations, vector fields, dynamical systems) can yield some insights. Inspired by viewpoints in recent work by @Xiaojie_Qiu et al. https://t.co/lhPi7EXfeZ

These systems are *not* machinesThe brain is not a circuitThe cell is not a mechanistic entityMolecular motors are not actual motorsEven modern software -- machine learning models -- have deviated from such machine metaphors

Modeling dynamic and large systems is not new and has been the backbone of complex systems/systems bio for a while, but now it's becoming pervasive and is fundamentally at odds on the main tool we've used to conceptualized systems for over a century: the machine metaphor https://t.co/206IpJSGSr

New post on https://t.co/AVNKZqoLuK on a convergence in how we model and conceptualize increasingly dynamical systems in biology and software. Cells, neurons, molecules, machine learning, causality, polygenic models all make an appearance.https://t.co/SF3D1hL0fA

It is complex and messy - this is the well trodden realm of epidemiologists and sociologists - and genetics can probably illuminate some things, for example using weak genetic effects as natural experiments (my other evergreen love of mendelian randomisation).

much of that diversity is as important (probably more important) about the societal / social differences associated with ethnicity - some of this is economic, some other aspects of our society, for example education.

So when we see differences on the basis of ethnicity between groups of people it is unlikely the main drivers of this is genetics - shifts in allele frequencies which are skewed between ethnicity *might* be part of explanation, and sampling a diverse set of people is important
...but... ethnicity classification is quite pervasive in our society, because of our behaviour - people's gestalt's assessment of other people and other people are consistent inside a society

These defy - make a mockery of - "ethnicity" of people as categories. It is just ... not how humans peopled the world; categories of humans just ... are a terrible way to think about human genetics and terrible way to think about humans overall.

And you can also see it in our population genetics, human archeology and the formation of our species - from physical sites that we discover showing movements of people and cultures, to our language sharing, to the way to trace individual histories via genetics

And this time perspective just goes back - Cape Coloureds, Goans... and then... Europeans as mixtures of founding people. The whole move, have children, move over the many generations have happened again and again by our species.

Another way to think about this is the common "Mixed race" ethnicity category in many systems. This sort of "its  a complicated" is not some small grouping of people - it is *all* of the Hispanic/Latinx grouping, and *all* of Afro-Caribbean; it is just a perspective time

(we can *force* a squish down into 2D PCA space or into some UMAP/tSNE 2D space, and this can sometimes vaguely correspond to ethnicity labels, but this squish is genetics => 2D => ethnicity labels and it is not reversible)

The dimensionality already shows the limits of this. One can sometimes reasonably go from genetics (~300,000 dimensions) => ethnicity (1 dimension, 10 bits). You can't go backwards. It just *doesn't work*.

Genetics on the other hand is a formally ~3 billion dimensional thing, but occupies thankfully a far small space (let's call it ~300,000 dimensions, around haplotype blocks; it's a complex beast) and it doesn't squish down easily beyond that.

Another way to think about this is that ethnicity classifications (themselves hugely different country to country) is a process of ticking boxes (sometimes writing in "other" line, which is then often not used). It's a 1-dimensional, ~10 bits of information about someone

(nor do we routinely socially hassle people who have red hair about "which part of Ireland are they from originally" or "what is your heritage" because... we culturally get that hair colour is just hair colour. We nearly always see the individual first, not the hair colour first)

There are many ways to think about this. One simple one is that skin colour genetics is not a million miles away from hair colour genetics (its a bit more complex, but not so much) and we don't think of hair colour as somehow definitive of the rest of the genome

Yet again Ethnicity != Genetics. (evergreen tweet). Despite the fact that skin colour is predominantly genetic, ethnicity classification, which often uses skin colour as part of the gestalt assessment of ethnicity is *not* a proxy for overall genetics

Our findings suggest Permo-Triassic land and marine extinction dynamics were likely quite different, underscoring the importance of understanding this extinction in specific places before making generalizations about the event.

The paradigm has been to use the marine extinction as a touchstone for timing the event on land which is less understood. So some studies struggled to time the land event with the marine extinction, concluding that in places like the Karoo land extinctions may not be related. https://t.co/FuCRXxdP8M

We don't yet know B.1.617's role in the current situation in India. And I think there is evidence that it's not as problematic as other VOCs. Time will tell, and in some sense it doesn't matter: don't panic, keep vaccinating, avoid risky tranmission situations where you can.
You can easily compare to other VOCs and VUIs at the very lovely https://t.co/J8UxgJmWS7

Also, 484Q has not turned up in experiments selecting better ACE2 binding (and hence infectivity) compared to 484K. Plus B.1.617 is missing N501Y, which is a key factor increased binding for other VOCs and VUIs.

In terms of mutations, most attention is on E484Q and L452R in Spike. Both have shown evidence of reduced neutralisation by some monoclonal antibodies. But vaccine induced immunity is polyclonal and involves T-cell response. So I think it's not that likely that it truly "escapes"

If we turn to the UK, must remember that nearly all positive tests from recently returned travelers are sequenced. @SMHopkins implied this morning on @AndrewMarr9 that v. large fraction of UK B.1.617 cases so far are travel related, which is consistent with other VOCs & VUIs.

Furthermore, this lineage has existed for months at low levels in India, and has been seen occasionally elsewhere. There's lots of caveats around different local conditions, but the fact that it hasn't grown sooner makes it likely to not be as transmissible as B.1.1.7 in my view.
(e.g. as @theosanderson tweeted, geographic distribution of sequences doesn't match case numbers in recent data https://t.co/rf4rbWUHfJ)

I don't know much about the sampling strategy of INSACOG, the group doing the sequencing, but with these numbers, lots of different biases could paint an inaccurate picture, and I would definitely not draw conclusions about cause and effect of the current wave without more data.

So what about spread? Well, I don't think we really know yet. B.1.617 has become more common in India at around the same time as the recent huge & tragic wave of cases, but <1000 sequences have been reported in GISAID out of ~4M cases since mid-February.

3 & 4 are very important (at the end of the day, arguably all that matters is vaccine efficacy), but take time, even when labs around the world are focusing on these questions. I haven't seen anything yet on B.1.617, so won't comment further.

In the "variant era", there are 4 kinds of evidence we can use to evaluate a new variant: (1) how fast it is spreading in different places, (2) pre-existing info about specific mutations it carries, (3) lab experiments (ACE2 binding, Ab evasion, etc), (4) real world vaccine data.

A few thoughts on the B.1.617 variant, first seen in India in late 2020, recently seen in >100 cases in the UK, and very much in the news here. TLDR: we should watch carefully, but I don't think any of our best lines of evidence on variants are yet cause for concern. üßµ

9/9 My speculative outlines are twitter threads like this one. This one was from a muse rather than from blocks in Roam. In either case, threads use the dopamine engineered by Twitter, but for creative work. Your instant feedback is gold. And it connects like-minded people.

8/ If you do most of your notes under Daily Pages, indented under relevant page refs, instead of the pages themselves, the silos of your life will inevitably meet each other.This seems to train your biological brain to also break its own silos. I've noticed this in myself.

7/ You can use your sidebar to line up blocks, pages or queries you could use to create a new string of ideas.Other features that help focus attention aside from the sidebar: hiding sections by collapsing children blocks, zooming in the block, filtering.

6/ As you write, indentation and link referencing encodes relationships between blocks that influences your future self's filters and queries.When you block ref instead of repeating yourself, you are being more efficient, and you enrich relationship between blocks.

5/ In Roam, you have to use shift-enter like a psychopath to avoid containing ideas in blocks.No discipline needed. You just write. It is okay if you don't ID blocks considered zettels. Your future self can just do a  search, filter or query & decide at the moment.

4/ Turns out, at this level of abstraction, I'm doing the same thing- the containers are blocks- they are strung together through 1) indentation, 2) link ref, 3) tags (shared linked ref), 4) block ref, 5) speculative outlining- Daily Pages break silos in Roam and in your mind

3/ Luhmann made the most of what was available to him- the containers were index cards- he strung them together through 1) physical arrangement, 2) references via unique card numbers, 3) the practice of laying them out as an outline- these practices broke silos among ideas
2/ As a practice, the Zettelkasten is essentially:- writing ideas in independent containers- have a practice of stringing together these containers- fabricate serendipity among these containers

Ophthalmologists perform sub-retinal injections day in and day out. Chemotherapy isn't required in this process to suppress the immune system, so less risk of 2ry complications. The closer you get Cas9 to the mutation, the better chance you have at repairing the problem. Period.
IMO this is one of the best delivery targets. The CEP290 gene occurs directly at the level of photoreceptors. Its function is to maintain cell transport and shape.

The longstanding obstacles of gene therapy and gene editing is target organ delivery. Science has since come a long way. My bullish thesis on $EDIT stems from the ability to deliver Cas9 directly to the photoreceptor via sub-retinal injection to correct the CEP290 gene.

The GS downgrade on $EDIT is a report rooted in trepidation based on opinion, not fact. Claiming Edit-101 may not generate enough productive editing to meaningfully improve patients' vision is an opinion that disregards the science of CRISPR-Cas9.

But we need to make government personal - we need to make government ours - to both give citizens a stake and a voice.  Government shouldn't be an 'other.'It should be a "we."It should be Human.And yes, we need to take back the power.
Reduce time wasted by citizens trying to figure out how to negotiate bureaucracy, reduce time wasted by fed employees dealing with frustrated, irate citizens who aren't being heard...

And if you think about it, this actually could be a cost-saving measure: the federal government currently employs millions, an additional 10K targeted directly at helping citizens( plus shared support staff) would actually help reduce waste...
In fact, I think this passage is the PERFECT inspiration for a council representing the diversity of the people of this nation.https://t.co/Q5FwT6x7TE

And for the numbers?  I'd actually propose that we look back to George Bush and Thomas Wolfe for inspiration...A citizen's council, providing ten thousand points of light.thoughts, @Peggynoonannyc ? https://t.co/IBByxvs5Ct

Eventually, new legislative responsibilities could be granted - i.e., the greater council could help to form official mandates for what issues the other legislative bodies address, establishing deadlines, etc. But EVERY citizen should have personal access to their reps.

To start, these 'councilpersons' could serve as lobbyists/liasons on behalf of the interests of the citizens they represent - taking some of the power from the hands of K street and distributing it to all citizens.

This would help to solve the problem with the lack of diversity of location-based representation, and would make more sense in a nation where work is remote and individual socioeconomic concerns are tied more to occupation than regional industry.

IOW, you have two senators (6y), one house rep, and one citizen council rep... ideally, where you are not required to vote annually for a council rep, but can register under your selected representative's office - and change at any time.

I'm also struggling to re-run a lot of code. Mostly because of compute (methods taking ~2-3 days on a GPU etc). Should we be re-running the code as reviewers?
Though with the code *and* methods, you can explore these conflicts in the review. Ocassionaly harmonising these in review has led to improved performance of the method.
This problem comes to life when the code differs from the stated methods. Are the methods mistaken or the code an old iteration? You only catch these if you *look* at the code
Methods are becoming sparser/poorly explained. I worry the plug-and-play nature means people aren't actually sure what they are doing. (This is often fixed during review)
Code is increasingly being supplied without having to ask for it. Most of the time its actually reasonably well commented etc.

Inspired by AUCell, we wrote UCell, an #RStats package designed for single-cell gene signature scoring, based on (Mann Whitney's) U statistic, that depends only on gene expression ranks in individual cells and is therefore not affected by dataset composition

For scRNA-seq analysis we use Seurat a lot because it's awesome. However, its gene module scoring function (AddModuleScore) produces inconsistent results for the same cell depending on the composition of the dataset, which is undesirable in many situations

Basically, that is like most virulence factors/markers for Listeria monocytogenes. In this large population, most proposed markers are strongly linked to the CC and not independent, which may be awkward for many of the surveillance studies looking at those factors. /6

For instance, CC1 has EssC1 (2968 out of 2968!), the devilish CC666 has EssC5, CC6 has EssC2, and these are next to each other on the cgMLST tree.An exception is CC14, which has a cluster of EssC5 and a cluster of EssC4, but mostly it is predictable which one will be there /5

As I have a cgMLST tree, MLST/clonal complex and high level isolation source info for all of them, checked distribution patterns.- no link with isolation source visible- very strong links with MLST clonal complexes/non-CC STs. Basically, CC and EssC type are linked /4

Had a quick look at one of the 106, and it has a EssC, but is different from EssC1-7. I assume these 106 genomes may yield some more EssC types. Distribution: Lineage I: 23 +1 neg, Lineage II: 69 + 1 neg, Lineage 3/4/innocua: 14. Of interest? /3

I split the search (at DNA level, 80% coverage, 80% identity for a positive score) into the conserved N-terminal bit, and the EssC1-7 specific C-terminal bits. I have 106 genomes where the N-terminus is there, but the C-terminus does not match EssC1-7. Two complete negatives. /2

In summary, we can sequence a human cell with long reads and detect genetic variation that otherwise is difficult to find! It would be great to get feedback on this and your thoughts on potential applications. And again, huge thanks to everyone involved!

Finally, we attempted de novo assembly of the genome from a single cell. Repetitive and chimeric reads were first removed (about half of the dataset!) and the remaining HiFi reads were assembled using #hifiasm. Results are summarized in this table https://t.co/g0sU7CWC12

With @PacBio reads we find a higher number of SVs (insertions, deletions and tandem duplications) as compared to the @Illumina single-cell data. We can be sure that most of these SV events are true because they were also found in bulk DNA

We called SNVs in the @PacBio data using #DeepVariant from @GoogleHealth. In this way we find about as many SNVs as for @Illumina ‚Äì but from much less sequence data! Some of the @PacBio SNVs were detected in ‚Äúdark‚Äù regions of the human genome https://t.co/IqU69lW9xR

Sequencing on @PacBio worked great! We produced around 20Gb of HiFi data for each T-cell and covered up to 40% of the human reference. The dMDA introduced a lot of intramolecular chimeras within the reads, but it turns out this is not a huge problem

The dMDA fragments were 9 kb on average, which is not too far from the sweet spot for @PacBio HiFi sequencing. Two individual T-cells were selected for library prep. We didn‚Äôt have enough DNA for normal #HiFi sequencing, so instead we used a low-input protocol

We evaluated the dMDA approach by @Illumina sequencing. Clearly dMDA gives more uniform coverage and better performance compared to a regular MDA. Likely because of limited reagents in each droplet, preventing extreme overamplification https://t.co/ySqPxUZpQg

T-cells from a human donor were used as starting material. Experiment outline: 1) Isolate an individual cell using FACS 2) Lyse DNA fragments and encapsulate in droplets 3) Perform dMDA 4) Library prep and sequencing. Steps 2 and 3 happens in the #Xdrop https://t.co/eUQQKSUVDB

A human cell contains only a few picograms of DNA. In order to sequence this, amplification is a must. We opted for droplet MDA (dMDA) using the @Samplix #Xdrop instrument. Why dMDA? Our hope was to reduce amplification bias and inter-molecular chimeras

Without the dedication of clinicians and patients involved in all the trials analyzed in this study, this research wouldn‚Äôt have been possible. We greatly thank them and made our codes and datasets publicly available for academic purposes (https://t.co/23SYgSQnUK).

SELECT is the first synthetic lethality-based precision oncology tool for analyzing the tumor transcriptome. It shows considerable accuracy across many different targeted and immunotherapy trials, laying a basis for future prospective transcriptomics-based clinical trials. https://t.co/LBX9kuzw3v

The attached figure illustrates reports that a clinician would receive from a SELECT analysis. Based on pre-treatment transcriptomic profiles of patients, an SL-score will be assigned to each drug, providing clinicians with personalized SL-based treatment options. https://t.co/HVfoUiLKdC

Evaluating this approach retrospectively in a recent WINTHER multi-arm basket clinical trial, we show that SELECT is predictive of the response and that the fraction of patients benefitting from treatments may possibly be markedly increased by targeting SL vulnerabilities. https://t.co/BiK1OKhv9p

Overall, through a retrospective analysis of 35 targeted or immunotherapy clinical trials of about 2,500 patients, SELECT is predictive of response in 28 out of 35 cases (80%) across 10 different cancer types. https://t.co/J9loNcLGhS

This collection includes a fresh pre-treatment transcriptomics profiles and treatment response data from Samsung Medical Center, where lung adenocarcinoma patients were treated with pembrolizumab (https://t.co/FXhfweybPn).

For checkpoint immunotherapy, SELECT is predictive of tumor response in 15 out of 18 clinical trial datasets with accuracy levels of AUC>0.7 and successfully predicts patient survival in 3 additional cohorts (Gide et al. also shows AUC>0.7 in addition to the survival signal). https://t.co/v3b8hyra39

For targeted therapy, SELECT is predictive of patients‚Äô tumor response in 7 out of 10 clinical trial datasets with accuracy levels of AUC of ROC>0.7 and successfully predicts patient survival in 3 out of 4 additional cohorts. https://t.co/8e3Vdc4hSk

SELECT prediction accuracy was tested on a large collection of 35 clinical trial datasets (spanning 14 targeted therapy and 21 immunotherapy cohorts across 10 cancer types), a scale markedly surpassing previous efforts to our knowledge.

The basic idea underlying the use of SLs for guiding patients is that a drug is likely to be more effective in patients where many of the SL partners of its targets are under-expressed in the tumor, thus leading to specific and selective tumor cell death. https://t.co/oWJTftivDE

*Synthetic lethality* (SL) is an interaction between a pair of genes, where their individual inactivation has no phenotype, but their co-inactivation leads to cell death. We identified the SL pairs from analyzing a large collection of patient cohorts of 10k tumors. https://t.co/N7wVveaMjZ

Current precision oncology mainly targets actionable mutations & has limited patient coverage. We present the first precision oncology framework that systematically guides cancer treatment based on *synthetic lethal* vulnerabilities identified via the tumor transcriptome.

We know from Israel and UK that the current vaccines in those countries work well against B.1.1.7. It is hard to piece together real world efficacy data on P.1 and B.1.351 as numbers are far far lower. I think we should know more this coming month but it is thin pickings.

However it may well be that severe (hospitalisation) disease is different from infection/transmission and that vaccines are more pan-variant effective at preventing hospitalisation. There is good theoretical reasons to think this as it will involve T-cell immunity.

The gnawing concern will be vaccine / immune escape variants, and we already have two ones with some differential immunity - P.1 (Brazil) and B.1.351 (South African) variants. Others are basically inevitable given the amount of transmission, the amount of immunity and vaccination

Across South America and Africa, two areas I have less of a deep understanding compared to Europe the epidemic is raging; it looks particularly bad in South America. I hope more vaccine supply can make it to these countries

Countries which have done well in suppression (Japan, South Korea) or elimination (NZ and Australia) have more time and less urgency, but I do worry that B.1.1.7 and other variants might change the epidemic too much (I hope not).

(basically the first countries have to probably feel out the right balance on relaxation with more care and caution whereas the soon to follow countries should have more confidence seeing practical examples being executed).

Personally I think it will be best to strengthen NPIs across Europe to control transmission (I was so glad to see France tighten before Easter) and simply hold this until vaccination, noting carefully the experience of Israel and then UK's relaxation to get an idea of timings

(Vaccination rates need to be high; vaccine hesitancy needs to be tackled and good communication around the very rare risks for blood clotting (Ox/Az) and, as previously noted in the clinical trials, anaphalatic shock (Pfzier) needs to be tackled)

Back to Europe, with vaccine production increasing, and increasing vaccination rates (delivery rates >> supply in most countries, which is the correct way around) the Israel and UK style endgames are within relatively easy reach this summer.

(and, as frustrating as it is, as with Israel now we will be walking on egg shells with some restrictions in 2021 even in best case scenarios for a variety of reasons; pockets of unvaccinated individuals and potential new variants with new biology still)

The "genome" consists of 9 number "genes". 1 to stay still, then 8 for different directions to turn. A random number determines the direction of movement in the next step, using the genes to determine relative probabilities.This doesn't provide much room for creativity.

In @GeneticsSociety's social issues and professional practice committee, we have been discussing the need for guidelines on the clinical use of polygenic risk scores and their (many) limitations. Seeing these claims makes me realize how urgently we need such guidelines. 6/n

I don't know how some @Stanford doctors could put their names behind this or how @US_FDA can allow such a product with overhyped claims, little clinical value, and clear potential for harm to get commercialized. Quite disappointing. 5/n

I am not even getting to everything that is ethically wrong with their claims, or technical issues such as using @illumina sequencing for preimplantation genetic testing based on DNA from a few cells. 4/n

& if you are of European ancestry, there is still little value in using polygenic risk scores to predict the risk of an unborn baby developing these complex diseases because they are heavily influenced by non-genetic factors such as diet, physical activity, lifestyle, etc. 3/n

If you are of non-European ancestry (e.g ~85% of the world's population), a polygenic risk score can tell you little about your genetic risk for these complex diseases because we simply don't know much about the genetic basis of these conditions in non-European populations. 2/n

An example of abusing science for profit. This company claims to use polygenic risk scores as a parental genetic testing tool to calculate the risk of having a child with 10 common, complex diseases or to select the embryos with the least risk. Our results show the value of STING-seq for functional characterization of GWAS variants at scale, and our power analyses show that hundreds of loci can be analyzed with feasible experiments. The biggest bottleneck for many traits may be availability of good cell lines! 6/6

Robust enrichment of independent GWAS loci in downstream networks of GFI1B and NFE2 is very cool: It suggests that hitting these pathways in different ways affects the GWAS trait, i.e. the effects converge at a network level. How generalizable is this? We don't know yet. 5/6

Finding a large number of trans-genes for 3 SNP loci (TFs GFI1B and NFE2 in cis) is an exciting view to pathway effects that are typically difficult to screen for. Note though that most cis effects didn't show up in trans genes - not everything is mediated via networks. 4/6

Usually but not always the cis-target gene was the closest one; usually we detected a single cis-target but also captured some regulatory pleiotropy; we found a cool example of 7 distinct GWAS hits in different CREs for the same gene. There's a lot of complexity to dig into! 3/6

I'll admit that I was (positively!) surprised by the high yield of STING-seq: cis target genes for 42% of 88 SNP loci that were selected by GWAS fine-mapping & CRE overlap. Notably, these weren't discovered by eQTLs, suggesting that this is highly complementary info. 2/6

Excited to share our preprint with @johnomix  @nevillesanjana & co, introducing STING-seq for CRISPRi+scRNA-seq analysis of GWAS target genes. John's thread is a mustüëá. Here are some of my reflections on lessons about functional architecture of GWAS: 1/6 https://t.co/Wwjx9Cqo4W

and asymmetric risk (you can only lose up to the premium). So you start doing your strategy on options. It works well. You turned your shitty 1% strat into a 10% returner. You're beating the market now.

Like maybe it returns 1% a year. But it's neutral. So what can you do? You lever it up. You go full degen. 500% levered total return swaps? We can do better. But why risk full ruin of your position? We have these things called long options. You have the benefits of leverage
(not '10 chromosomes', but '10 columns'!)

Couple this with a market with substantial acceleration of returns, and it's much harder to beat the market with a conventional strategy. Momentum and other factors have been crowded, so returns are getting *worse* over time. Let's say you have a shitty market neutral strat.

This is simply because if you imagine a 100x levered position, a 1% move can basically wreck you. That's your leverage ratio. He has a good thread on it. So when volatility declines, you can simply lever up more. It's risky in a high-VIX environment, but makes sense in a low one.

Does all this matter?  As time goes on, perhaps no one cares what happened in VC during March 2021.  But it IS important to get this right.  We need to check to see if policy changes are having the desired effect.  We can't just hope it will all work out.10/10

The VC trace pops above 40 when the window no longer includes the problematic days.  So what was the actual rate of new cases during this time?  No one knows.  Probably closer to the state average.9/10

Why wasn't the CA doubling time not affected?  At no time did the corrections exceed the new cases, the total always was higher than the previous day.  This impacts the average number of new cases too: artificially lower than they should have been.8/10 https://t.co/kgOFuaGFy3

This graph shows why the @CAPublicHealth got it wrong.  The model breaks down: error bars are huge.  Doubling time estimates are impacted if the rolling average includes ANY of the affected days.  All an artifact of incorrectly applying corrections to the total case number.7/10 https://t.co/ckuwVlKmFU

I've reported before about why it is important to correct errors in the new case numbers in the right way. By applying corrections in a few days (3/10 to 3/17), the total number of cases went down. To calculate doubling time, the total number of cases cannot go down.6/10

Typically, this property is precisely what researchers hope to capture when assessing heterogeneity, and so it justifies the complexity of the model necessary to compute CDI, CMDI, and CADI.

CDI is particularly appealing because of its simplicity. It addresses, ‚ÄúIf I randomly select a cancer cell from my sample, how uncertain am I about the cell subpopulation from which it arose?‚Äù This definition has been helpful in sketching the intuition for collaborators.

Finally, metrics are valid only when there exists a clear link between them and biological properties of interest. SDI lacks this. MATH has an intuitive connection, but it's wrong. CDI, CMDI, and CADI are imperfect, as any measure must be, but they succeed in this regard.

Second, look at your damned data. A VAF histogram confers way more information about heterogeneity than a summary stat like MATH. Sure, you can play games with your histogram bin sizes to tell different stories, but it's harder to fool yourself this way than with a summary stat.

So, after all that, what do we conclude? First, summary statistics can mislead. They try to depict a complex picture of heterogeneity with a single number. We explicitly demonstrated how MATH can mislead. CDI & co. are not exempt, of course, but they're more resistant to it.

Finally, it was just a *really badly put together report* (I've skimmed read it, and dived into bits). Honestly. Just in terms of *having a proper report* it was full of bad stats, bad history, bad literature discussion and bad written english. Bad content and bad delivery.

It requires listening and discussion, it requires respect of people's view points, it requires good data and statistics, and it requires changing viewpoints from history and myth making around countries - finding new stories to weave into the British (English!) tapestry.

In this the major question must be how we improve this for everyone, above all disadvantaged groups, but everyone benefits in a fairer society where everyone's talents can be expressed and people live happy(ier) lives.
It is clear by epidemiology (statistics) and lived experience that we still have a society with considerable structural racism - discrimination on visible differences associated with ethnicity.

This is how we make a better society for everyone; it has to be a multi-step journey, and we can both look back and see how far we have come and then turn forwards and see the mountains we still have to climb. Our progress should lift us, but doesn't mean the journey has ended.

I like the commentators such as @sundersays on the politics and society; the stoic politeness and engagement of @DavidLammy and the communication of @AdamRutherford as three examples of how to build bridges and understanding.

Furthermore too much is framed as part of a divisive culture war component that tries to align politics into the picture in a two-sided, confrontatial manner. It is so depressing to read and see so much discourse being wasted on these topics.

But, moving away from my expertise, I am truly dispirited at the way the recent Race report frames things - it neither did a good job of the epidemiology (from my epidemiology friends) nor history (from my amateur historical perspective).

(In summary - "ethnicity" and "human genetics" are really distinct things, and although there are some links in the way that ethnicity uses visible differences, notably skin colour, actually they are best thought of as two distinct concepts- ethnicity nearly all a cultural one)

Next steps could for example include actually observing staggered sweeps, for examples using Relate+CLUES.

Disease genes with a high recombination rate and low numbers of disease variants do not have any sweep deficit, while those with low recombination rates and high numbers of disease variants have a very strong sweep deficit.

We then tested if Hill-Roberston interference between advantageous and deleterious variants can explain the sweep deficit at disease genes, and found that the deficit is indeed strongly dependent on the rate of recombination and on the number of disease variants.

@DiChenlu first found a strong deficit of selective sweeps  at human disease genes. The next question was what could possibly explain the pattern. We thought at first it could be higher pleiotropy, but found no strong evidence in favor of it explaining our results.

If you are interested in evolutionary medicine, ckeck out @DiChenlu's recent preprint on how interference between advantageous and deleterious variants may have strongly decreased strong recent adaptation at human non-infectious disease genes:https://t.co/qHcZ7Hz1qq

üö®Critically, most of these emergence events would likely have been unsuccessful, as beautifully described by @jepekar and colleagues in this paperüëá.Importantly, though, all of this remain speculation.https://t.co/XaQvh7nEEN

üö®However, the epi data combined with the genomic data where we see evidence of "A" and "B" lineages circulating in different markets early in the outbreak would be consistent with a "multi market" hypothesis of multiple spillover events from animals to humans.

The "A" lineage may be a more appropriate root for the SARS-CoV-2 tree as I previously speculated üßµüëá, but we observe many reversions in the SARS-CoV-2 genome, so this question remains open.https://t.co/I29FmskciP

SARS-CoV-2 already being "highly adapted to humans" right after it emerged - as has been suggested by e.g., üëá - was a failed statement from the get go, but we likely also didn't manage to capture early divergence of the virus right after its emergence.https://t.co/vEWfJqSGHQ

While "B" was (and is) the most dominant lineage, most of the early sequencing was focused on the Huanan market, likely leading to us missing early transmission events - and we almost certainly missed most early post-emergence transmissions.
This *could* suggest multiple introductions into humans or one lineage evolved into the other in the human population - we don't know. https://t.co/HeOIx5GPhX

Interestingly, if we look at SARS-CoV-2 genomic data from early in the outbreak, it splits into the "A" and "B" lineages - the latter being found at the Huanan market and there is one example of "A" at another market. https://t.co/Z8v4fX8Xw1

The report follows up on 168 cases, 93 of whom had been to a market, about half of which visited the Huanan market. The first cases reported at that market were visitors, but overall, more vendors were identified to be COVID-19 cases in the beginning. https://t.co/XbyoTBiTC4

If we look at the early cases, it's clear that many / most of them were associated with the Huanan market, however, several other exposures - including the first known case on December 8 - visited a different market. https://t.co/J6fZTGQjRR

457 animal-related samples from 188 individuals of 18 species were also collected and tested - however, all of them were negative. As for human exposures at the market, most of them were in vendors and SARS-CoV-2 genomes from environmental samples matched those found in humans https://t.co/aWBSQA5R6h

To look for direct evidence of SARS-CoV-2 at the market, 923 environmental samples were collected out of which 69 from the Huanan market were positive for the virus, including from cages. The vast majority (~90%) were found in the part of the market where animals were sold. https://t.co/xny2VHyRUe

Combined, these data show that SARS-CoV-2 was not circulating widely prior to the outbreak in December. While the resolution isn't sufficient to exclude potential low-level circulation of SARS-CoV-2, recent speculation that there was early widespread transmission is unfounded.

The team also screened tens of thousands of animal samples (serology + qPCR), but again, all samples were negative. They also looked at purchases at pharmacies during the pre-outbreak period - all normal, with no increase. https://t.co/3g5F51MNkC

They also looked at excess mortality before, during, and after the outbreak, and found that it wasn't elevated prior to the second week of January in Wuhan. In Hubei province outside Wuhan, excess mortality was not elevated throughout. https://t.co/kKEYoKKL0d

To see if SARS-CoV-2 was circulating prior to December, 2019, they looked at epidemiological data and tested thousands of banked samples using qPCR (active infection) and serology (prior infection) from individuals between Oct - Dec with influenza like illness. All negative. https://t.co/ngD6UKb9UW

To answer the first question, the researchers looked at several lines of evidence - some of it old, much of it new:- ILI- Serology- pharmacy purchases- qPCR testing on retrospective suspected cases- Sequencing- Excess deaths

Two open questions:1. Did SARS-CoV-2 circulate (widely) prior to the (known) outbreak?2. Was the Huanan market the nucleation point of the pandemic?New data in the report answer both of these - "no" and "yes", respectively.

We hope our study will serve as a roadmap for future research to tease apart the complex relationships in various lineages of flowering plants. (11/n)

We hope our study will serve as a roadmap for future research to tease apart the complex relationships in various lineages of flowering plants. (11/n)
Our study showed that the relationships between polyploidy, dysploidy, and lineage diversification vary a lot within and across major lineages of flowering plants. (10/n)
We found polyploidy was better correlated with lineage diversification than dysploidy (and in turn better than chromosome number loss and chromosome number gain). (9/n)

But both those types of rates shared a common source of estimation error, clade age, which may lead to false correlations. We got around this issue by estimating their relative importance instead. (8/n)
Next, we asked whether the rates of polyploidy and dysploidy were correlated with the rates of lineage diversification. Indeed, they were! (7/n)

We found the rates of chromosomal evolution across flowering plants varied by two to three orders of magnitude. An impressive 400 to 4,000 fold difference across orders and families!!! Lots of variation in the rates of polyploidy and dysploidy to explore in our figures! (6/n)

Importantly, previous large-scale studies examined the flowering plants as a whole rather than individual clades like we did here. That allowed us to appreciate the heterogeneity of the rates of chromosomal evolution across flowering plants. (5/n)

To tackle these questions, we conducted the largest phylogenetic analysis of chromosome numbers across flowering plants to-date. In all, we analyzed ~30,000 taxa, of which ~16,000 had chromosome counts belonging to 46 orders and 147 families of flowering plants. (4/n)

How do the rates of polyploidy and dysploidy (loss in chromosome number and gain in chromosome number) vary across flowering plants? Are the rates of polyploidy and dysploidy correlated with the rate of lineage diversification? (3/n)
We examined the rates of chromosomal evolution across flowering plants and related the two major processes of chromosomal evolution - polyploidy and dysploidy - to lineage diversification. (2/n)
